betterquesting.name: Worms Are Good
betterquesting.desc:
Silworms are great! You can only get them by using a crook on the leaves, and they will occassionally drop a silkworm. Use that silkworm on the leaves and watch them "infest" your leaves. Then, use the crook again to get string!

You can also cook them for a tasty treat!

betterquesting.name: Getting the Good Stuff
betterquesting.desc:
The almighty Sieve! It can sift through dirt, gravel, sand, dust, crushed netherrack, and more to give you all the goodies you need to rebuild your world!

To use, just insert a filter and then right click with the block you want to sieve in your hand.

betterquesting.name: Go Get Me a Sapling
betterquesting.desc: To get your first sapling, simply check the quest above this one!

betterquesting.name: String
betterquesting.desc: Use the worm from the previous step to infest leaves. A fully infested leaf block will spread the worm infestation 1 more block. Over time, your entire tree will become infested.Be careful though, because you will not get any saplings from infested leaves. Always make sure to keep at least one sapling behind!

betterquesting.name: Mesh
betterquesting.desc: There's a lot of things you can do with the newly gained String, but your first priority should be to make something that will sift through dirt to get the really good stuff. For that, you're going to need a Silk Mesh. You're going to need 3 of them to get started.

betterquesting.name: The Start of Tinker
betterquesting.desc:
Now that you have some templates, you're going to need to do something with them. Use the Stencil Table to create new templates. Use the Part Builder to, well, build parts. Finally, use the Tinkers Tool Station to assemble and modify your tools.

Helpful hint: If you line them all up in a row, then you'll be able to access all the respective blocks through the tabs at the top.

betterquesting.name: Porcelain Bucket
betterquesting.desc:
You're going to need to move liquids around, including liquids that are extremely hot(like lava). Wooden bowls are not well suited for transporting lava, so you're going to need something a little more temperature tolerant.

First, create an unfired bucket using 3 Porcelain Clay, then put that bucket in a furnace to get a fired Bucket.

betterquesting.name: Go and hit a tree
betterquesting.desc: With your sapling, you can start to grow some trees. If you just plant the tree and walk away(or, well, as far away as you can on a 3x3 island) then you'll be waiting a very long time. Try crouching multiple times to make the tree grow faster. Then, puch tree, get wood!

betterquesting.name: Crafting Table
betterquesting.desc: Ummm, it's a crafting table... simple as that!

betterquesting.name: Cobblegen!
betterquesting.desc:
As I said before, you're going to need a cobblestone generator. The concept of a cobblegen is rather straightforward, you need to place a lava source block 1 block away from water, but the water can not touch the lava, otherwise the lava will turn to obsidian. So, with that in mind, place a water source block down and let one side flow down so you have running water. Leave an empty space between the flowing water and place the lava down. The lava will flow towards the running water and turn into Cobblestone.

Oh, and in case you missed it before, lava will burn anything it can, so don't make your cobblestone generator out of wood.

betterquesting.name: Storage
betterquesting.desc: Well, at this point, your inventory might be getting a bit crowded. To help you with this problem, you should craft some chests.

betterquesting.name: Do You Have the Stones?
betterquesting.desc: Well, not much to say about this one... It's Cobblestone!

betterquesting.name: Barrels O' Fun
betterquesting.desc: Barrels are helpful in many ways. First of all, you can throw leaves, saplings, apples and other fermentable things in there to make more Dirt. Second of all, you can leave them out in the rain and they will collect water, which you can then collect using a bucket. And finally, if a barrel is full of water, then you can put some Dust in there and it will turn into Clay.

betterquesting.name: Getting Dirty
betterquesting.desc: With the barrel loaded full of leaves, sapling, and other things, you can start making dirt.

betterquesting.name: Volcanic Ash
betterquesting.desc: Hammer Sand to get Volcanic Ash

betterquesting.name: The Kits To start
betterquesting.desc:
Welcome to All the Sky

If this is your first time playing a modded minecraft skyblock map, this guide will try to show you how it all works. If you're an experienced skyblock player, some of the quests may appear to be bit bit too grindy, but I do ask that you pay attention anyway, because you may learn something new.

As always, the first step is to get wood by punching trees...

betterquesting.name: Bigger Chest
betterquesting.desc: Did you ask for a bigger chest? Well, here you go!

betterquesting.name: Burn Baby, Burn
betterquesting.desc: Well, with all that cobble you're getting, might as well make a furnace. You're going to need it to progress anyway.

betterquesting.name: There's a Light...
betterquesting.desc:
By now, your base must be getting bigger. Those few torches we gave you earlier are probably not enough to cover the whole ground. Why don't you go ahead and craft a few torches to get some lighting going on.

Hit F7 to see where your light may be low. Anything with a yellow dot on it means mobs can spawn at night. Anything with a red dot on it means mobs can spawn at any time.

betterquesting.name: All Cobbled Up
betterquesting.desc: By sieving dirt, you get Small Stones. 9 of those in a crafting table will make 1 cobblestone.

betterquesting.name: Stop... Hammer Time!
betterquesting.desc:
Hammer Cobblestone to get Gravel. Hammer Gravel to get Sand. Hammer Sand to get Volcanic Ash. 

Stop... Hammer Time!

betterquesting.name: Going Through the Crucible
betterquesting.desc:
You're going to need lava, and the best way to do that is to use the crucible. The crucible will slowly melt 4 Cobblestone into 1 bucket of Lava if the crucible is over a heat source. Heat sources include Torches, Lava, and an Open Fire(use a Flint and Steel on Netherrack to create an infinite flame source). Each heat source has different melting speeds, so you might want to move the crucible on top of something better as soon as you can.

To create the crucible, first you'll need to make an Unfired Crucible using 7 Porcelain Clay in a U shape. Then, place the Unfired Crucible in the furnace to get a regular Crucible.

Oh, and if you built your platform out of wood, you might want to keep the lava or open flame as far away as possible! (Unless, of course, you just like to watch the world burn)

betterquesting.name: Spores
betterquesting.desc: Spores come from sifting sand through a sieve. Spores are incredibly useful because with them, you can create Mycelium. More will be covered once you have attained your first spore.

betterquesting.name: Compressed Gravel
betterquesting.desc:
Yes, you can compress Gravel. 

If you put this is a Heavy Sieve, you can sift through 9 blocks of Gravel at a time. 

You can also hit it with a Compressed Hammer to get 9 blocks of Sand.

betterquesting.name: Compressed Sand
betterquesting.desc:
Yes, you can compress Sand. 

You can sieve this in a Heavy Sieve to sift through 9 blocks of Sand at once. 

Just like with the Gravel counterpart, you can also whack this with a Compressed Hammer to get 9 Volcanic Ash.

betterquesting.name: Compressed Volcanic Ash
betterquesting.desc:
Yup, you can even compress Volcanic Ash. 

Just like Compressed Gravel and Compressed Sand, if you put this in a Heavy Sieve, you can sift through 9 blocks of Volcanic Ash at a time.

However, whacking this with a Compressed Hammer does nothing.

betterquesting.name: Compressed Cobble
betterquesting.desc:
Compressed Cobble is a great way to save on inventory space. Plus, it'll come in handy later when you get the more advanced Hammer.

Pro Tip: If you have a crafting table open, hover your mouse over any uncompressed cobble and press <shift> + K.

betterquesting.name: Bigger Hammer
betterquesting.desc: The regular hammer is nice and all, but you really don't want to spend all your time hammering down all the things you're going to need. So, craft yourself one of these, then whack some Compressed Cobblestone and notice you get 9 Gravel back! You can then do the same for any compressed material.

betterquesting.name: Are you calling me a Crook?
betterquesting.desc: Simply breaking leaves with your hand(or whatever tool happens to be in your hand) is not going to get you very many Saplings, and let's face it, you're going to need a lot of Saplings. To get you started, build this Crook!

betterquesting.name: To Get Started
betterquesting.desc:
Welcome to the wonderful world of Actually Additions. This mod contains many things. Too many things to list in a simple intro, so let's get started. 

The first thing you're going to need is a piece of Black Quartz.

betterquesting.name: Dirty Power
betterquesting.desc: It's a Coal Generator. Nothing special. Put Coal in, and power comes out. It also works with Charcoal.

betterquesting.name: Get a Faster Crook
betterquesting.desc: The standard crok is slow. You'll need something that will go a bit faster! Take 4 crooks and put them in an upside-down L shape and you'll get something that will go a bit faster.

betterquesting.name: Porcelain Clay
betterquesting.desc: You're going to need to get a cobble gen up and running at some point, which means you're going to need some lava, and a way to move that lava around. Porcelain Clay will help you get what you need.

betterquesting.name: Mycelium
betterquesting.desc:
The most basic usage of Mycelium is to allow mushrooms to grow at any light level, but perhaps one of the more useful features of Mycelium is that if you put a Barrel full of Water near a Mycelium block, the water will turn into Witchwater. If you put sand into Witchwater while the witchwater is still in the barrel, then you'll get Soul Sand.

Pro tip: Don't place a bucket of Witchwater in the overworld. It will spawn Ghasts and then you'll have to fight those Ghasts... and let's face it, you're not prepared to go up against an angry horde of Ghasts at this point... or maybe you are!

betterquesting.name: Atomically Reconstructing Things
betterquesting.desc:
The Atomic Reconstructor is the core machine for this mod. It allows you to create the various crystals you will need in order to continue.

It does take power, and depending on what it is re-constructing, that could be a little power or a lot of power.

The way you use it is by placing it so that is faces a block. It will eventually fire a pulse if given power and if the block the pulse hits is something that can be reconstructed, then it is transformed. It will also transform items around it, like redstone or coal that has been dropped on the ground, so just be aware of that.

By default, it is set to continually pulse. Simply right clicking on the Atomic Reconstructor with a Redstone Torch will change it so that it requires a redstone pulse. Place a button down next to it, then start crytallizing!

betterquesting.name: Energy Transfer
betterquesting.desc:
Transfers energy from point A to point B. Use the wrench to link two energy relays together. 

They can transfer power over large networks, without the need for wires.

betterquesting.name: Wireless Water(Patent Pending)
betterquesting.desc: If you ever need to move liquids from one place to another, then this block is perfect for you. Of course, who would want to do such a silly thing.

betterquesting.name: Wrenched!
betterquesting.desc:
Because every mod needs a wrench, this mod is no different.

It's a wrench, it does things when you click on other things.

betterquesting.name: Restonia
betterquesting.desc: Simply drop some Redstone in front of the Atomic Reconstructor.

betterquesting.name: Compressed Dirt
betterquesting.desc: So what are you going to do with all your new found dirt? You could, of course, make a farm, plant a few trees, or you could gather 9 of them in a crafting grid to create Compressed Dirt.

betterquesting.name: Growing Hunger
betterquesting.desc:
By now, your hunger bar may be looking rather thin(unless you've been eating all your rewards). By sieving Dirt, you have a chance to get all sorts of seeds. By planting these seeds on tilled dirt, you can get wheat...

I sense another quest following this one...

betterquesting.name: Making Bread
betterquesting.desc:
Bread is filling, but be careful, if you eat too much of it, all the benefits of all that saturation will go away. You'll need to vary your diet with whatever other edible things you can think of.

Bread is a good start though!

betterquesting.name: Bulk Processing
betterquesting.desc: The standard sieve is nice and all, but we can do this faster. Try putting together one of these sieves! You can only use compressed gravel, sand and other items, and you do loose a bit in the process, but the speed is well worth it!

betterquesting.name: Stronger Mesh
betterquesting.desc: You may have noticed that the durability of the Silky Mesh leaves a lot to be desired. If you're going to be sieving a lot(which you will) then you're going to need something a bit stronger.

betterquesting.name: Stronger Barrel
betterquesting.desc: Wooden barrels are great, but they can't hold lava. We need to put lava in barrels for the next part.

betterquesting.name: Obsidian
betterquesting.desc: Obsidian is useful for many crafting recipes, so we're going to need a way to synthesize it. By placing a bucket of lava in a Stone Barrel, then placing some water above the barrel, that will make obsidian for us. The best part is we don't have to mine it!

betterquesting.name: Natherrack
betterquesting.desc: To get Netherrack, all you need to do is fill a Stone Barrel with lava, then right click it with a piece of Redstone. Viola!

betterquesting.name: Soul Sand
betterquesting.desc: Soul Sand is a tricky one to get. First of all, you need to make sure you place a barrel down next to some Mycelium. Fill that barrel with water and wait. After a certain amount of time, the barrel will convert the water inside to Witchwater. Once you have the Witchwater, just right click with a piece of Sand and that will give you Soul Sand.

betterquesting.name: End Stone
betterquesting.desc: If you've done Netherrack, then you'll know how this goes. Put a bucket of lava into a Stone Barrel and then right click with a piece of Glowstone to get yourself a block of End Stone.

betterquesting.name: It's Like One Giant Storage Chest!
betterquesting.desc:
Item relays are a complicated topic. so much so that there is no way I could introduce the power of the Item Laser Relay, combined with the Inventory Interface in one simple introduction. This is one of the few times I have to say you absolutely need to read the manual.

Put simply though, an Item Laser Relay connected to multiple storage chests acts as one giant inventory to an Inventory Interface.

betterquesting.name: Tinker's Template
betterquesting.desc: It's time to get you started on thinking about what kind of tools you may need...

betterquesting.name: Auto Sorting
betterquesting.desc: Much like the basic Item Laser Relay, there is no way I could explain what is capable with the Advanced Item Relay. You really should read up on what it can do!

betterquesting.name: Captain, We Need More Power!
betterquesting.desc:
If the basic energy relay isn't enough to satisfy your energy requirements, try this block out. It can transport a significantly more amount of power.

It should be noted the there is an even more powerful version if you still need to transfer even more energy around.

betterquesting.name: Clay
betterquesting.desc:
Place a few barrels somewhere in the open where rain can fall on it, or, alternatively you can just put water in by using buckets, but I'm going out on a ledge here and assuming you don't have a bucket for the first time you'll be doing this. Then, wait for rain.

Once it rains, the barrels will fill with water. Place some Volcanic Ash in with the water to get clay.

betterquesting.name: Auto-Placing
betterquesting.desc:
Ever wanted the ability to automatically place blocks somewhere? Well, now you can.

As with most other Actually Additions blocks, this one has two modes that can be switched by right clicking it with a redstone torch. The default mode is the deactivation mode, where a redstone signal will stop it from placing items. The other mode is pulse mode where it will only place items when it receives a redstone pulse.

betterquesting.name: Auto-Breakage
betterquesting.desc:
It breaks blocks and stores the blocks in the internal inventory. Nuff said.

This is perfect for automating those early game cobble generators. It doesn't require power and it will just keep going until its internal inventory is full.

betterquesting.name: Fluid Collecting
betterquesting.desc: Same as the Block Breaker, but for liquids. Try placing this in front of an infinite water source and see what happens!

betterquesting.name: Canola MKI
betterquesting.desc: Canola can be a powerful energy source, especially early to mid-game. If you place the canola in a press and then ferment the output, it creates oil, which will give you a substantial power output.

betterquesting.name: Remote Breaking
betterquesting.desc:
There may be situations where you can't quite put down a block breaker. In those cases, we've got you covered with a Phantom Block Breaker. Place it down, then using the Phantom wrench, right click to select the block you want to be broken, then right click on the Phantom Block Breaker to set that block. 

It works even through walls of Reinforced Obsidian!

betterquesting.name: It's Like Magic!
betterquesting.desc:
Placing items in the world... remotely!

This block is pure awesomeness! You can use it for Wither Spawners, TNT placers, etc... The sky is the limit(no, literally, because you can't place anything beyond the sky limit).

betterquesting.name: Coils
betterquesting.desc: With a few pieces of Restonia, you'll be able to craft your very first Coil. Coils are used in a lot of the machines, so be prepared to make a lot of them if you're going to be making a lot of machines.

betterquesting.name: Fluid Placing
betterquesting.desc: Much like it's block placing counterpart, this will place fluid in the world. Very handy for those canola oil farms.

betterquesting.name: Grindy
betterquesting.desc: Grind your ores into dust, then cook those dusts to get double the amount of ingots you get from cooking ores.

betterquesting.name: Smelty
betterquesting.desc: Why have one item cooking at a time when you can have two!

betterquesting.name: Void
betterquesting.desc: Simply drop some Coal in front of the Atomic Reconstructor.

betterquesting.name: Palis
betterquesting.desc: Simply drop some Lapis Lazuli in front of the Atmomic Reconstructor.

betterquesting.name: More Machines, Please
betterquesting.desc: So the advanced coil is really easy to craft, but it gives you access to the next tier of machines and capabilities of the mod.

betterquesting.name: Canola MKII
betterquesting.desc:
Okay, so the default Canola works fine and all, but there's an even more powerful version of it. Simply place oil in the world and then drop a Crystallized Canola Seed in it and that will create Crystallized Canola, which will give you a substantial power boost.

To get the Chrystallized Canola Seed, just place it in front of an Atomic Reconstructor.

betterquesting.name: Canola MKIII
betterquesting.desc: And for the ultimate in Canola Power, you're going to need an Empowerer. Once you get the Empowered Canola Seed, simply place down a bucket of Chrystallized Canola Oil and drop the seed in and now you have Empowered Canola.

betterquesting.name: Oil!
betterquesting.desc:
With your newly found Canola, you're going to need to process it into oil. These machines will hlp you do that.

Place the Canola in the Canola Press, then place the Fermenting Barrels down next to it. It should automatically pipe the Canola Oil into the Fermenting Barrel, and you can then pipe the output of the Fermenting Barrel directly into an Oil Generator.

betterquesting.name: Power For the Masses
betterquesting.desc:
Okay, so we made some oil, and now we want to make that into power. Well, here's how you'll do just that.

Simply make the Oil Generator, then find a means of piping the Oil from the Fermenter to the Oil Generator, then you'll be making power!

betterquesting.name: This Is Not A Drill
betterquesting.desc:
This drill is awesome. It uses power to drill, and doesn't take any durability damage. It can accept upgrades to it that will increase its speed and radius. You can set this drill up to mine 1 block, 3x3 blocks, or 5x5 blocks at various speeds.

To install the upgrade, just shift+right click with the drill in your hand.

betterquesting.name: Portable Power
betterquesting.desc: It's a battery. It does what batteries do. It stores energy, but it also distributes it's stored energy to items in your inventory.

betterquesting.name: Display Stand
betterquesting.desc: The Display Stand does exactly what it's name implies. It displays things. However, it can also do things as well. Certain items will work in the display stand if the display stand is given power. For more information on that, I refer you to the manual.

betterquesting.name: Empower To The People!
betterquesting.desc:
The Empowerer is the final tier of crafting mechanics for Actually Additions. Put this block down, and place 4 display stands around it leaving 2 blocks between the Empowerer, and then place item on the Empowerer and the Display Stands and watch the magic happen. It's well worth noting that the Empowerer does not require power, but the Display Stands do.

And just when you think you can't ever have too many particle effects!

betterquesting.name: Phantomface
betterquesting.desc:
Okay, let me try to explain this without confusing you. Place this block down, then right click a chest or some other inventory somewhere else with a Phantom Connector, then right click the Phantomface. Now, that Phantomface will act as though it is that inventory. Confused?

It's super handy when you want to use an inventory, but all of it's sides are covered or inaccessible. Now, where did I leave that Blood Altar...

betterquesting.name: Phantom Redstoneface
betterquesting.desc: Just like the Phantomface, but for redstone.

betterquesting.name: Phantom Energyface
betterquesting.desc: Just like the Phantomface, but for energy.

betterquesting.name: Phantom Liquiface
betterquesting.desc: Just like the Phantomface, but for fluids.

betterquesting.name: Shiny Things
betterquesting.desc: Now that you have an Empowerer, you can make all sorts of nifty gadgets. Trying making a few Empowered Crystals first!

betterquesting.name: Remote Control
betterquesting.desc:
Ever wish you could set up a system to automatically keep a certain amount of items in your inventory at all times? Ever wish you could automatically repair/replace your armor? Well, now you can.

This block can remotely place or remove items from your inventory. When combined with the ESD, you can specify which slots certain things go in. Would you like to be able to have different configurations if you're going into battle versus if your just out building? Well, now you can.

betterquesting.name: Fix It Til It's Broken
betterquesting.desc:
This is maybe just a little overpowered. 

It can repair most things that take damage. Combine this with a Player Interface, and your armor will never get a scratch on it!

betterquesting.name: Enori
betterquesting.desc: Simply drop some Iron Ingots in front of the Atomic Reconstructor.

betterquesting.name: Automated Farming!
betterquesting.desc: Okay, now we're talking. A block that will farm in a 9x9 area in front of it. It does use a considerable amount of power, so I hope you have something better than a Coal Generator to back it up.

betterquesting.name: Drop It Like It's Hot
betterquesting.desc: There may be times when you'll need to automate dropping things into the world, and this block will let you do just that.

betterquesting.name: Ranged Collection
betterquesting.desc:
Need the ability to automatically pick up things that have been tossed on the ground? Then this is your guy!

Very handy for mob farms. Just remember to set it to blacklist mode!

betterquesting.name: Chopping Trees
betterquesting.desc:
You can create one of these nifty blocks to help you out early game. 

Progressive Automation, as it's name implies, is a mod where you progress to different tiers of machines. You have to use the current level machine to make the next level machine and so forth. However, it's worth noting that the only difference between the tiers is the type of tools they can use. A wooden machine can only take wooden tools, and a stone machine can take wooden tools as well as stone tools. The benefit of this is that as you progress, the tools will last longer and longer.

Since all it takes to make this level is some cobble and some wood, you should be able to get started at this level fairly easily.

betterquesting.name: Farming for Dummies
betterquesting.desc: Tired of having to go over to your farm to harvest your crops? Well, then, this is the block for you. Place this underneath the dirt block, feed it with some fuel, and give it a hoe, and you're all set to go. You can easily extend the range of this by adding in upgrades.

betterquesting.name: Extra Utilities
betterquesting.desc: ExtraUtils2 has some automatic item transfer capabilities with filtering. To get started through, you're going to need to get an Ender Pearl. Good luck!

betterquesting.name: Starting Automation(WIP)
betterquesting.desc: Simple tools to get you started!

betterquesting.name: Tinker's Construct(WIP)
betterquesting.desc: Can I get a crossbow for my birthday?

betterquesting.name: EnderIO(WIP)
betterquesting.desc: You're going to need a lot of ender pearls!

betterquesting.name: Mekanism(WIP)
betterquesting.desc: Time to get started on your ore processing!

betterquesting.name: Industrial Craft(WIP)
betterquesting.desc: Wait, don't put that nuke there...
